WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:06.000
I'm Rachael Dempsey. I lead Customer Marketing at Posit.

00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:11.000
I guess about four and a half years ago, we started something called a Data Science Hangout,

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:16.000
where every single Thursday we get together online as a community,

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:20.000
and we have a different featured leader join us as our guest.

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:25.000
Matthew Montero, Chief Data Officer at GenRe, has been one of those featured leaders before,

00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:29.000
so I'm excited to have him here in person too.

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:32.000
But if you haven't had a chance to join the Hangout before,

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:37.000
if you're listening virtually and want to get back together with this amazing group of people,

00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:42.000
every single Thursday, Libby Heron now hosts the Data Science Hangout.

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:46.000
She's the real host now.

00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:48.000
I'm sure she's sharing the link right now in Discord,

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:51.000
but you can also just Google Posit Data Science Hangout,

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:56.000
and you can join us from 12 to 1 Eastern Time every single Thursday,

00:00:56.000 --> 00:00:58.000
unless it's a holiday.

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:05.000
But for today, because we are in person too, if you want to ask questions, just raise your hand,

00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:08.000
because the thing about the Hangout is it's all powered by you,

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:11.000
so all the questions are audience-based.

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:14.000
But you can also ask things anonymously too,

00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:19.000
so in the Positron Lounge channel in Discord, put questions in there.

00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:24.000
I have my phone, I just remembered, and I will look at Slido to ask it.

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:27.000
But to get us started, Matthew, would you be able to introduce yourself,

00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:31.000
share a little bit about your role, and something you like to do for fun too?

00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:32.000
Great, great.

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:36.000
Yes, so I'm Matthew Montero, Chief Data Officer of Genree.

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:37.000
First of all, what is Genree?

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:40.000
Genree is a global re-insurance organization.

00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:44.000
We write about $14 billion of business.

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:49.000
Again, we're globally, so we have to think about everything we do both in North America

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:53.000
and throughout Europe, Asia, and other countries.

00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:58.000
And so we sit within global IT,

00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:02.000
so we focus on how we enable technology throughout.

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:06.000
So this might be all the way from data science components,

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:12.000
but also data reporting, data engineering, and data governance, of course.

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:19.000
My background actually started off as an actuary on the NCCI,

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:22.000
which is a workers' counter rating bureau.

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:29.000
And I started there just as an actuary trying to learn about utilizing R at that time,

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:32.000
and then that's when I got introduced with RStudio at that time.

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:35.000
And it just grew out to something bigger than that.

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:39.000
I eventually created an analytics group within that organization,

00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:44.000
and then brought that on to Sanofi, which is a pharmaceutical company, a global one,

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:47.000
where I got my first taste of what it means to be a global company.

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:49.000
And eventually moved on to Generate.

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:53.000
What about for fun?

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:54.000
Yes, for fun.

00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:59.000
So I do have four kids, so four, six, eight, and ten years old.

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:04.000
And that takes up all the rest of my time of my daily life.

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:11.000
But they are very active, so we do soccer as well as running.

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:18.000
So every single week I basically run six miles to keep my daughter up to speed with her endurance.

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:20.000
That's awesome.

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:23.000
So can you tell us what it means to be a chief data officer?

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:24.000
Yes.

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:31.000
So one of the key aspects is being able to take IT jargon

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:35.000
and be able to communicate that to the business, but mostly related to data and technology.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:42.000
So one of the key things was bringing in what we call enterprise data architecture.

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:47.000
So having a way to be able to get data out of these applications,

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:50.000
anything you write in Tree, type into applications,

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:53.000
and try to get data out of there, and do something with it.

00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:58.000
And it's not as simple as just pulling something, manipulate it, and spread it out somewhere else.

00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:02.000
You've got to have an actual, defined process around that.

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:05.000
So that's one of the things that I do.

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:09.000
Well, how do you define that? How do you support it? Keep it up and running.

00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:15.000
After you put something into production, midday or midnight, something might go wrong

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:18.000
because Australia is using it in their day-to-day life,

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:22.000
and who's going to be up there waking up to be able to support that?

00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:24.000
So we had to create that production support model.

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:29.000
One wing within this area, again, is data science.

00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:34.000
So we do want to look at how do we do new tooling, how do we do new products,

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:39.000
how do we build capabilities to allow actuaries, underwriters,

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:44.000
or anyone to be able to create applications, demonstrate, do POCs.

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:47.000
But building out where we can have a guardrail around that,

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:50.000
meaning that we want them to be safe with whatever they're trying to do.

00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:56.000
So meaning not accidentally sharing data outside of our network,

00:04:56.000 --> 00:05:00.000
making sure we have enough guardrails to make sure that doesn't happen.

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:05.000
So usually during the data science hangout, I get to see the chat that's happening, too,

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:10.000
and see everything behind the scenes instead of being here on a stage.

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:14.000
So I just wanted to see in the room, are there any questions so far,

00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:17.000
anything you want to ask to Matthew?

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:21.000
Because I can keep asking my questions, but it's all powered by you, too.

00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:25.000
So as you have a question that comes to mind, just wave at me.

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:26.000
There you go.

00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:38.000
And if you can repeat the question just so people hear virtually, too.

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:42.000
As a data scientist, the most challenging part I had in my career

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:47.000
was putting something into production, something that was...

00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:49.000
Okay, so let me give you a little back story.

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:54.000
The part I was in at NCCI was part of an economics group,

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:56.000
and they basically generated models.

00:05:56.000 --> 00:05:58.000
And my job was to take those models, productionalize it,

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:01.000
create an application or create a report around it,

00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:06.000
and be able to work with the actuaries to actually use that in their day-to-day work.

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:11.000
But a challenging part was going from something that is model-based,

00:06:11.000 --> 00:06:13.000
it was based on Bayesian modeling,

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:15.000
to something that you're looking at averages,

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:18.000
and three- or four-year rolling averages,

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:19.000
and they're used to that.

00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:21.000
And how do you incorporate those two?

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:23.000
How do you explain how that works?

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:26.000
And what I found, a lot of it is, one, education,

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:31.000
and getting more used to your regular work,

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:34.000
but then, two, it's change management.

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:36.000
We all are going through this now with AI,

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:40.000
or earlier on with analytics, is that it's going to happen,

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:43.000
it's just how do you explain from a leadership,

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:45.000
so top-down perspective, and also from a bottom-up perspective,

00:06:45.000 --> 00:06:48.000
how do you get people used to it and get on board with it?

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:51.000
And then once they start using themselves and see that it actually is beneficial,

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:55.000
then that's when you start the snowball effect.

00:06:55.000 --> 00:06:56.000
Thank you.

00:06:56.000 --> 00:06:58.000
I see Marlene has a question.

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:02.000
I wish I could call on Marlene to come in here and ask it.

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:03.000
But hi, Marlene.

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:08.000
Marlene asks, what has your career trajectory been like leading up to CDO?

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:12.000
Is this a role you saw yourself taking earlier in your career?

00:07:13.000 --> 00:07:15.000
Actually, right when I was leaving college,

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:22.000
I was up to college, I was wanting to be an actuary.

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:24.000
I was always about math, statistics,

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:27.000
and then when I started my career,

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:31.000
during my schooling, I also did mechanical engineering,

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:32.000
so I had a programming background.

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:34.000
We were required to understand Java, C+,

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:36.000
and then with statistics, we learned R.

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:39.000
So I came in with three different languages.

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:44.000
And because of that, they got me into this economics track as well

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:47.000
to work with code to build things.

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:51.000
And that's what I got for my first taste of technology.

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:52.000
I was like, this is actually pretty interesting.

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:53.000
It got more and more interesting.

00:07:53.000 --> 00:07:57.000
And then I started thinking, oh, these actuarial processes we have,

00:07:57.000 --> 00:07:59.000
we use Excel, we use all this stuff,

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:01.000
and we can simplify this or we can automate pieces of this.

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:03.000
And I built it using R.

00:08:03.000 --> 00:08:06.000
And so that got me more and more interested.

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:12.000
So at that point, I knew that I didn't want to be an actuary much anymore.

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:14.000
Because one, exams were tough.

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:16.000
I did get through exam five.

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:19.000
To get to exam six, you get your first credential.

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:25.000
I think the percentage of passing is 50% every single time you get to your next exam.

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:27.000
So if you can do the math, it gets pretty difficult

00:08:27.000 --> 00:08:29.000
on how many people actually get through all of them.

00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:33.000
And so then I got really into, well, then I got into technology.

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:35.000
I went back to get my master's degree in computer science.

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:39.000
And then I learned more and more about why technology is the way it is.

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:44.000
And then that's when I shifted away from actuarial type of position

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:46.000
to more of an analytics position.

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:51.000
So when I moved to Sanofi, I was the global analytics lead.

00:08:51.000 --> 00:08:53.000
And so building an analytics team,

00:08:53.000 --> 00:08:59.000
and all focused on how to work with the business to create products.

00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:03.000
And then at that point, and I learned more about leadership at that point,

00:09:03.000 --> 00:09:07.000
because I had to push against or push to leadership.

00:09:07.000 --> 00:09:09.000
We need to expand, we need to do more,

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:13.000
because, well, I get all these requests in business, but we're only so big.

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:15.000
And then that's when I learned that, well,

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:17.000
there's different flavors of leadership,

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:22.000
and I needed something different on my trajectory.

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:24.000
So then when I moved over to Genree,

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:29.000
I was given that opportunity where we're a very lean organization.

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:32.000
We only have 100 IT staff,

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:37.000
and essentially you're a fish in a very small pond.

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:40.000
So it's very easy, as long as you do very well,

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:42.000
and have a goal, and have strategic vision,

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:45.000
it's a very good, easy way to move up.

00:09:45.000 --> 00:09:48.000
For someone making that jump into leadership,

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:53.000
do you have any book recommendations or resources to point us to?

00:09:53.000 --> 00:09:55.000
Yes, there is.

00:09:55.000 --> 00:09:58.000
There's another book I'll try to remember throughout this today,

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:06.000
but there's one, Seven Habits of Effective Leadership.

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:10.000
Yes, highly effective leadership.

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:15.000
So that book actually was a very big game changer for me.

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:18.000
And it was more, not really about the actual seven itself,

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:25.000
but it was one of them that focused on that the only thing that someone,

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:28.000
when someone impacts you, so say someone makes you sad,

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:30.000
or makes you happy, or whatever,

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:34.000
it's you yourself who actually allows that impact to happen.

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:37.000
So meaning, they're not forcing you to be sad,

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:39.000
they're not forcing you to be upset,

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:40.000
you're allowing that to happen.

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:42.000
And the moment I really realized that,

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:45.000
everything changed in my perspective of how to lead,

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:47.000
how to live day-to-day life,

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:49.000
and I incorporate that everywhere I do now.

00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:51.000
Thank you.

00:10:51.000 --> 00:10:54.000
I'll be checking for any hands raised in the room too.

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:58.000
But I see Bartos asked a question here on the Slido,

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:02.000
and it's, how do you actually convince actuaries

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:05.000
to stop using Excel and start using R?

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:11.000
So the way we did it, pre-the company,

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:15.000
was that we actually got a lot of actuaries to start learning R.

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:19.000
And we got to a point, I think it was around 2022,

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:22.000
people who were part of this what we call actuarial programming team,

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:25.000
that were building with R code.

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:27.000
And so that I think was starting a,

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:29.000
I don't know what ended up happening,

00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:31.000
I was there for 10 years,

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:35.000
I think it was like year 8 that we started this group,

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:38.000
but I don't know what ever happened to the end of that.

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:40.000
But at that point it was growing,

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:41.000
and a lot more people were using it,

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:42.000
seeing the benefits of it.

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:43.000
Like a community group?

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:46.000
Yeah, we built a community group within the organization.

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:48.000
And so they started using it more.

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:50.000
And so I think that's one piece of it,

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:52.000
is just building community, getting that to work.

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:54.000
And we did the same thing in January,

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:58.000
we built, we have an internal R group as well,

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:01.000
where we share what we build, how we build it,

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:03.000
and any challenges people have around.

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:05.000
So they do have a community there too.

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:08.000
How did you first get them interested in like,

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:10.000
switching from Excel to R?

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:13.000
Yes, so I was at the time,

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:16.000
one or one of two R programmers there,

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:18.000
that have actuarial background.

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:20.000
So in the beginning,

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:22.000
so it was just me building these applications,

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:24.000
and showing how we can automate certain things.

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:25.000
And people got interested in it,

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:27.000
and they're like, oh this is neat, this is cool,

00:12:27.000 --> 00:12:28.000
I want to do this too.

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:29.000
Because they did get interest,

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:31.000
all the way up to the chief actuary at the time.

00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:35.000
So that's, you do want to get that person's interest.

00:12:35.000 --> 00:12:38.000
And so I think it kind of snowballed at that point.

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:40.000
So from showing and telling.

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:41.000
Yep, show and telling.

00:12:41.000 --> 00:12:42.000
Kylie.

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:44.000
So sort of along the same lines,

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:45.000
this community building,

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:48.000
so what formats do you find worked well,

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:50.000
and how did you kind of maintain it?

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:52.000
Because it's easy to start a community actually,

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:55.000
but it's harder to maintain it as you grow.

00:12:55.000 --> 00:12:59.000
Right, so we had a dedicated individual,

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:01.000
who was in charge of overseeing the community.

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:03.000
So that was one big thing,

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:04.000
it's a community of dedication.

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:06.000
You also need the support of both the business side,

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:08.000
and also the IT side.

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:11.000
So IT is going to be there to keep it up and running,

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:13.000
making sure the features are available,

00:13:13.000 --> 00:13:15.000
to make sure that if you have challenges,

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:17.000
is it a just you challenge,

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:20.000
or is it a challenge that you have across everyone else,

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:22.000
to be able to get it connected to different systems,

00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:24.000
to make it just work very well for everyone.

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:28.000
But then from, so you need that hook into the community,

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:30.000
but then also on the business side,

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:31.000
you need to make sure you get the people

00:13:31.000 --> 00:13:34.000
who are the champions of the tooling.

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:36.000
So we're a global company,

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:39.000
so we want to look for people who are in Germany,

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:40.000
we want to look for people who are in the US,

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:42.000
we want to look at people that are in Singapore.

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:45.000
And that way, because then they will keep on

00:13:45.000 --> 00:13:46.000
promoting the product.

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:47.000
They're already champions,

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:48.000
that means that they're already interested

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:50.000
in telling people about it,

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:52.000
but if you get them empowered within the community

00:13:52.000 --> 00:13:53.000
to have a better voice,

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:56.000
to have a better channel to be able to communicate that,

00:13:56.000 --> 00:13:58.000
then it helps a lot.

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:01.000
I think it is so important to have someone

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:04.000
who is dedicated to building that community,

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:08.000
but I know it's so hard to convince your company

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:10.000
that you might need somebody for that role.

00:14:11.000 --> 00:14:12.000
Do you have any tips for that?

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:14.000
Yeah, so it's homegrown.

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:22.000
So for us, the RStudio Positive came in on the IT side.

00:14:23.000 --> 00:14:26.000
That was one of my first things when I came into Genu

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:28.000
was bring in Positive and support it and build it.

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:31.000
So it was bringing in someone who actually has a background

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:34.000
in that platform and in the language.

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:37.000
And then from there,

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:41.000
I brought in some people who can help build a community.

00:14:41.000 --> 00:14:44.000
And then eventually brought in Chris Engelhardt

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:47.000
also to oversee after I was done overseeing the area,

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:48.000
Chris overtaking that.

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:51.000
And the idea is that you need someone who has a pull

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:54.000
to be able to fix things that the community might bring up

00:14:54.000 --> 00:14:56.000
because if community brings up challenges

00:14:56.000 --> 00:14:58.000
and no one actually does a fix it,

00:14:58.000 --> 00:15:00.000
it kind of dissolves the community.

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:03.000
But also is if people want more,

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:09.000
a way to present or be appreciative of what they've built

00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:10.000
and other people see what they've built,

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:12.000
this is another venue to do that.

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:15.000
It is a lot of effort to curate an agenda all the time,

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:19.000
to be able to send out the notices,

00:15:19.000 --> 00:15:20.000
how the cadence is,

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:24.000
making sure that the community runs effectively.

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:27.000
But we took a lot of what you were doing,

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:29.000
the format and whatnot,

00:15:29.000 --> 00:15:30.000
we tried to do something very similar to that

00:15:31.000 --> 00:15:34.000
because it works and it works on a much bigger scale.

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:39.000
And so we just look at where do we see examples elsewhere.

00:15:39.000 --> 00:15:42.000
We do tend to see a lot of the same people presenting,

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:44.000
but that's okay because other people are listening.

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:46.000
But we do try as much as we can

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:48.000
to get other people to present as much,

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:50.000
especially when we hear on the side,

00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:51.000
oh, this person's working on this,

00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:54.000
oh, great, let's present this.

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:55.000
Thank you.

00:15:55.000 --> 00:15:57.000
Arsena?

00:15:57.000 --> 00:16:00.000
Arsena, what are some of the ways that you all get folks

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:05.000
who maybe are reluctant or maybe less interested in presenting,

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:08.000
what are some of the ways that you get them engaged?

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:11.000
Are there any common things that you do?

00:16:11.000 --> 00:16:12.000
And I can repeat a little bit

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:14.000
in case people can't hear virtually,

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:16.000
but it was about how do you get people engaged

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:21.000
or wanting to present, essentially.

00:16:21.000 --> 00:16:24.000
Yes, so one of the things is

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:27.000
we can work with those individuals to help build a deck,

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:29.000
and we'll be fine presenting ourselves.

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:31.000
We ideally would like them to present

00:16:31.000 --> 00:16:33.000
because it's their work, it's their product,

00:16:33.000 --> 00:16:36.000
or it's their vision, but it's okay.

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:38.000
If they're okay with it, we can present,

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:41.000
then we can mention that this came from this individual,

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:43.000
but then we can present for them

00:16:43.000 --> 00:16:45.000
because, again, it's about sharing.

00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:48.000
We want to be able to share across all these different ideas

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:52.000
and features that people are coming up with

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:54.000
and give an opportunity for it to be heard

00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:57.000
because we don't want people reinventing the wheel.

00:16:57.000 --> 00:17:01.000
We want people to kind of construct things together.

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:04.000
I see Libby asked a question over here on Slido,

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:06.000
and it's, do you miss coding?

00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:08.000
What advice would you give to someone

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:11.000
who loves the technical work and doesn't want to lose that

00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:14.000
in order to take on a leadership role?

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:16.000
Yes, that's funny because it was yesterday

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:18.000
that I got my first notice

00:17:18.000 --> 00:17:21.000
that I have not touched Pauza for 30 days.

00:17:21.000 --> 00:17:23.000
And in our company, if you do that,

00:17:23.000 --> 00:17:26.000
you actually lose your license within the next 30 days,

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:28.000
which is a sad moment.

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:30.000
That's the first time ever I've gotten that.

00:17:30.000 --> 00:17:33.000
But no, I do miss coding.

00:17:33.000 --> 00:17:36.000
I haven't encoded as much as I used to.

00:17:36.000 --> 00:17:39.000
Even when I started at Genry,

00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:42.000
I did code a lot for the first few years.

00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:44.000
I actually built presentations,

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:46.000
did my R markdowns at the time,

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:49.000
came up with how to create websites and all that.

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:53.000
But lately, I have a bigger team

00:17:53.000 --> 00:17:55.000
that can support that and build that.

00:17:55.000 --> 00:17:58.000
I can roughly draft things out,

00:17:58.000 --> 00:18:00.000
and I can send it over to them and say,

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:02.000
can we build this?

00:18:02.000 --> 00:18:04.000
I try to, at least in my mind,

00:18:04.000 --> 00:18:06.000
how I work constructively with code,

00:18:06.000 --> 00:18:08.000
because to me it's very important

00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:10.000
to have an engineering mindset.

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:13.000
So in an organization that I oversee,

00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:16.000
every single person who directly reports to me

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:18.000
has an engineering background.

00:18:18.000 --> 00:18:20.000
This is a requirement.

00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:22.000
And it's because of that

00:18:22.000 --> 00:18:25.000
that we are much more of a structured way

00:18:25.000 --> 00:18:27.000
in terms of how we communicate,

00:18:27.000 --> 00:18:29.000
how we come up with thoughts,

00:18:29.000 --> 00:18:32.000
how we come up with solutions.

00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:34.000
And I think it's that engineering mindset

00:18:34.000 --> 00:18:35.000
you get that from.

00:18:35.000 --> 00:18:37.000
Yes, I'm very open with that, very creative.

00:18:37.000 --> 00:18:38.000
I'm fine with that,

00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:40.000
but it's that being creative

00:18:40.000 --> 00:18:42.000
and having engineering part of you,

00:18:42.000 --> 00:18:44.000
it's then how you communicate that

00:18:44.000 --> 00:18:45.000
back to everyone else.

00:18:45.000 --> 00:18:47.000
Everyone else will understand.

00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:49.000
So going back to yes,

00:18:49.000 --> 00:18:51.000
I do miss coding a lot,

00:18:51.000 --> 00:18:53.000
because I did like creating new things.

00:18:53.000 --> 00:18:55.000
I'd be the first one to test out

00:18:55.000 --> 00:18:56.000
these different packages

00:18:56.000 --> 00:18:57.000
and build something with it

00:18:57.000 --> 00:18:59.000
and be able to demonstrate that to people.

00:18:59.000 --> 00:19:00.000
But now I get to enjoy

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:02.000
watching other people do it.

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:04.000
The question I had for you is,

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:06.000
I've talked to so many people from the community

00:19:06.000 --> 00:19:08.000
who have this challenge

00:19:08.000 --> 00:19:10.000
of communicating with IT sometimes,

00:19:10.000 --> 00:19:13.000
and the disconnect between IT

00:19:13.000 --> 00:19:16.000
and business data science users,

00:19:16.000 --> 00:19:18.000
and it feels like that's something

00:19:18.000 --> 00:19:20.000
that isn't a problem at Genry,

00:19:20.000 --> 00:19:22.000
and I'd just love to hear a little bit about that

00:19:22.000 --> 00:19:24.000
or what advice you have for us.

00:19:24.000 --> 00:19:25.000
I would say,

00:19:25.000 --> 00:19:27.000
I think it's just a general problem

00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:30.000
or challenge that you're going to have,

00:19:30.000 --> 00:19:31.000
regardless of the company,

00:19:31.000 --> 00:19:33.000
regardless of the organization set up.

00:19:33.000 --> 00:19:35.000
And it's just because

00:19:35.000 --> 00:19:37.000
it's a telephone thing that happens, right?

00:19:37.000 --> 00:19:38.000
So you're going to have

00:19:38.000 --> 00:19:39.000
one group of individuals

00:19:39.000 --> 00:19:41.000
who know what they want

00:19:41.000 --> 00:19:43.000
or think what they know what they want,

00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:44.000
and they're going to use

00:19:44.000 --> 00:19:46.000
some plain language,

00:19:46.000 --> 00:19:48.000
business-oriented language,

00:19:48.000 --> 00:19:50.000
and then they hand it off to someone else.

00:19:50.000 --> 00:19:51.000
But then that someone else

00:19:51.000 --> 00:19:52.000
is not in their mindset,

00:19:52.000 --> 00:19:53.000
doesn't have the same background,

00:19:53.000 --> 00:19:55.000
doesn't have the same knowledge

00:19:55.000 --> 00:19:56.000
in terms of their business processes,

00:19:56.000 --> 00:19:59.000
so there's going to be loss in language.

00:19:59.000 --> 00:20:01.000
And the same happens all the way around

00:20:01.000 --> 00:20:02.000
when the IT folks

00:20:02.000 --> 00:20:04.000
want to speak to the business side.

00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:06.000
And that's why

00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:07.000
I think when you have someone

00:20:07.000 --> 00:20:09.000
who came from the business,

00:20:09.000 --> 00:20:10.000
became IT,

00:20:10.000 --> 00:20:11.000
or someone in IT

00:20:11.000 --> 00:20:12.000
came to the business

00:20:12.000 --> 00:20:13.000
and learned the business side,

00:20:13.000 --> 00:20:15.000
that's when you're going to get that interpreter.

00:20:15.000 --> 00:20:17.000
And that's going to be key

00:20:17.000 --> 00:20:19.000
for any type of change management,

00:20:19.000 --> 00:20:22.000
any type of project

00:20:22.000 --> 00:20:24.000
where you're trying to

00:20:24.000 --> 00:20:25.000
work very closely together

00:20:25.000 --> 00:20:27.000
because you want to build something new.

00:20:27.000 --> 00:20:29.000
It is a very,

00:20:29.000 --> 00:20:30.000
I think it's a difficult task.

00:20:30.000 --> 00:20:32.000
It's something I still work on

00:20:32.000 --> 00:20:34.000
because I'm,

00:20:34.000 --> 00:20:35.000
all these new concepts,

00:20:35.000 --> 00:20:36.000
like with the whole AI stuff,

00:20:36.000 --> 00:20:39.000
like this is a very

00:20:39.000 --> 00:20:41.000
complex type of thing to describe

00:20:41.000 --> 00:20:42.000
and all the different levels

00:20:42.000 --> 00:20:43.000
of generative AI.

00:20:43.000 --> 00:20:44.000
It went from generative AI

00:20:44.000 --> 00:20:46.000
to agentic AI.

00:20:46.000 --> 00:20:47.000
And trying to explain that

00:20:47.000 --> 00:20:50.000
to a non-technical people

00:20:50.000 --> 00:20:51.000
to understand that

00:20:51.000 --> 00:20:52.000
and then understand it

00:20:52.000 --> 00:20:53.000
from all the media we hear

00:20:53.000 --> 00:20:55.000
and try to mix it all together,

00:20:55.000 --> 00:20:57.000
it's a lot of work.

00:20:57.000 --> 00:20:58.000
And so you're technically

00:20:58.000 --> 00:21:00.000
on the IT side of the house, right?

00:21:00.000 --> 00:21:01.000
Yes, yes.

00:21:01.000 --> 00:21:02.000
So if a data scientist

00:21:02.000 --> 00:21:05.000
comes to you with a new

00:21:05.000 --> 00:21:06.000
package or use case,

00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:08.000
how does that go?

00:21:08.000 --> 00:21:10.000
How do you work together?

00:21:10.000 --> 00:21:11.000
I have two things.

00:21:11.000 --> 00:21:12.000
So the first part is

00:21:12.000 --> 00:21:13.000
when I actually started at Genery,

00:21:13.000 --> 00:21:14.000
I just want to add a little piece,

00:21:14.000 --> 00:21:15.000
is that when I started at Genery,

00:21:15.000 --> 00:21:18.000
I introduced myself as

00:21:18.000 --> 00:21:21.000
previously an actuary first

00:21:21.000 --> 00:21:22.000
for my technical background.

00:21:22.000 --> 00:21:23.000
And the reason for that

00:21:23.000 --> 00:21:24.000
is to build that relationship

00:21:24.000 --> 00:21:25.000
with the business side.

00:21:25.000 --> 00:21:27.000
So that's one thing I did do

00:21:27.000 --> 00:21:29.000
from the beginning.

00:21:29.000 --> 00:21:30.000
But,

00:21:30.000 --> 00:21:31.000
what was the actual question?

00:21:31.000 --> 00:21:32.000
Sorry.

00:21:32.000 --> 00:21:34.000
Well, I'm just thinking about

00:21:34.000 --> 00:21:36.000
how do you actually go about

00:21:36.000 --> 00:21:38.000
working together?

00:21:38.000 --> 00:21:39.000
Like a lot of us are remote,

00:21:39.000 --> 00:21:41.000
at remote organizations too,

00:21:41.000 --> 00:21:42.000
and how do you build

00:21:42.000 --> 00:21:44.000
those stronger relationships?

00:21:44.000 --> 00:21:45.000
It's a lot of conversations.

00:21:45.000 --> 00:21:47.000
So I do a lot of,

00:21:47.000 --> 00:21:49.000
so when we do,

00:21:49.000 --> 00:21:51.000
my whole area works remote,

00:21:51.000 --> 00:21:53.000
so the whole IT actually

00:21:53.000 --> 00:21:56.000
is a remote team.

00:21:56.000 --> 00:21:59.000
And the,

00:21:59.000 --> 00:22:01.000
one second.

00:22:01.000 --> 00:22:03.000
Oh, there's some audio playing.

