00:22:25.000 --> 00:22:27.000
So that's a norm for us.

00:22:27.000 --> 00:22:29.000
But it's a lot of having

00:22:29.000 --> 00:22:30.000
a lot of meetings.

00:22:30.000 --> 00:22:32.000
And I know that

00:22:32.000 --> 00:22:34.000
there's the idea that

00:22:34.000 --> 00:22:36.000
sometimes there's too many meetings.

00:22:36.000 --> 00:22:37.000
But I think it's more of those

00:22:37.000 --> 00:22:38.000
one-on-one meetings that matter.

00:22:38.000 --> 00:22:39.000
That's where you build a relationship.

00:22:39.000 --> 00:22:41.000
That's where people get to know you

00:22:41.000 --> 00:22:43.000
and be able to understand your thinking

00:22:43.000 --> 00:22:45.000
or be able to start building that trust.

00:22:45.000 --> 00:22:46.000
And so that's where

00:22:46.000 --> 00:22:48.000
I think it's very important for

00:22:48.000 --> 00:22:50.000
to be able to have that communication.

00:22:50.000 --> 00:22:51.000
To know that

00:22:51.000 --> 00:22:53.000
when a business side is telling me something,

00:22:53.000 --> 00:22:55.000
I can translate that appropriately

00:22:55.000 --> 00:22:57.000
to the rest of the team.

00:22:57.000 --> 00:22:59.000
It's a trust thing.

00:22:59.000 --> 00:23:01.000
There was an anonymous question in Slido

00:23:01.000 --> 00:23:02.000
that was,

00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:04.000
what advice do you have for organizations

00:23:04.000 --> 00:23:06.000
who can do sophisticated research

00:23:06.000 --> 00:23:08.000
and create good one-off models,

00:23:08.000 --> 00:23:12.000
but don't yet have the infrastructure skills needed

00:23:12.000 --> 00:23:15.000
to be able to deploy that, essentially?

00:23:17.000 --> 00:23:19.000
So the first question would be,

00:23:19.000 --> 00:23:21.000
are you ready to support it

00:23:21.000 --> 00:23:22.000
whenever it crashes?

00:23:22.000 --> 00:23:24.000
So sometimes there are models

00:23:24.000 --> 00:23:26.000
in which it's okay.

00:23:26.000 --> 00:23:28.000
During business hours,

00:23:28.000 --> 00:23:30.000
it's only ran a couple times a year

00:23:30.000 --> 00:23:31.000
or a couple times a month.

00:23:31.000 --> 00:23:33.000
And then no one needs to worry about support.

00:23:33.000 --> 00:23:34.000
That's perfectly fine.

00:23:34.000 --> 00:23:36.000
It's only when you think about

00:23:36.000 --> 00:23:38.000
moving into something that needs full support.

00:23:38.000 --> 00:23:40.000
It's something you're going to have up and running

00:23:40.000 --> 00:23:41.000
24-7.

00:23:41.000 --> 00:23:42.000
Somebody might ping in.

00:23:42.000 --> 00:23:44.000
Someone might need to use it.

00:23:44.000 --> 00:23:45.000
And if it fails,

00:23:45.000 --> 00:23:46.000
who's going to support it?

00:23:46.000 --> 00:23:48.000
That's only when you really have to think about that.

00:23:48.000 --> 00:23:51.000
Now, there are a lot of from a...

00:23:51.000 --> 00:23:53.000
And I can't remember the packages off the top of my head anymore.

00:23:53.000 --> 00:23:54.000
I used to.

00:23:54.000 --> 00:23:56.000
But there's a lot of packages out there

00:23:56.000 --> 00:24:00.000
that at least build you a CICD pipeline

00:24:00.000 --> 00:24:02.000
or help you build a CID pipeline.

00:24:02.000 --> 00:24:04.000
And ensure that you at least have

00:24:04.000 --> 00:24:06.000
some type of rigid process in there

00:24:06.000 --> 00:24:08.000
to elevate things from your dev tests

00:24:08.000 --> 00:24:10.000
and QA into prod.

00:24:10.000 --> 00:24:12.000
And at least you can have some structure around there.

00:24:12.000 --> 00:24:14.000
So at least you have version control and all that.

00:24:14.000 --> 00:24:16.000
So I would suggest go that route

00:24:16.000 --> 00:24:18.000
to at least have that in the minimum.

00:24:18.000 --> 00:24:22.000
And then only when you need to consider

00:24:22.000 --> 00:24:26.000
about supporting it more than your business hours,

00:24:26.000 --> 00:24:29.000
then you need to think about the infrastructure.

00:24:29.000 --> 00:24:31.000
The infrastructure does take time.

00:24:31.000 --> 00:24:33.000
