in a world of trying to push the production

00:24:57.000 --> 00:25:00.000
and trying to build out as much as you can.

00:25:00.000 --> 00:25:01.000
Right.

00:25:01.000 --> 00:25:03.000
So it's finding...

00:25:03.000 --> 00:25:04.000
So if you're the only one...

00:25:04.000 --> 00:25:06.000
And quick for virtual.

00:25:06.000 --> 00:25:09.000
The question was around building up an analytics team

00:25:09.000 --> 00:25:11.000
for the first time, too.

00:25:11.000 --> 00:25:17.000
So there's two routes that happened through my career.

00:25:17.000 --> 00:25:20.000
One was I was essentially the sole person,

00:25:20.000 --> 00:25:24.000
and then I just built examples of solutions

00:25:24.000 --> 00:25:26.000
and then started a snowball effect

00:25:26.000 --> 00:25:27.000
that people started learning

00:25:27.000 --> 00:25:30.000
and started building their products.

00:25:30.000 --> 00:25:31.000
So that was one way.

00:25:31.000 --> 00:25:32.000
Because then you start getting people's buy-in,

00:25:32.000 --> 00:25:34.000
and then people are going to start building a team,

00:25:34.000 --> 00:25:36.000
and then you start getting bigger.

00:25:36.000 --> 00:25:37.000
So that's one way of building.

00:25:37.000 --> 00:25:40.000
The other way is finding the champions.

00:25:40.000 --> 00:25:43.000
So if your company is big enough,

00:25:43.000 --> 00:25:44.000
you can be like,

00:25:44.000 --> 00:25:46.000
oh, anyone else is interested in R,

00:25:46.000 --> 00:25:48.000
who are the R programmers here,

00:25:48.000 --> 00:25:50.000
who are people who have been doing this for a while.

00:25:50.000 --> 00:25:54.000
And then you can easily find out who are the champions,

00:25:54.000 --> 00:25:56.000
who are the ones who are wanting to learn

00:25:56.000 --> 00:25:58.000
or interested in learning.

00:25:58.000 --> 00:26:00.000
And then you start bringing them together.

00:26:00.000 --> 00:26:02.000
So it would be very much of that informal,

00:26:02.000 --> 00:26:04.000
ground-roots way of doing it.

00:26:04.000 --> 00:26:06.000
But it works.

00:26:06.000 --> 00:26:10.000
We actually built an AI team as well,

00:26:10.000 --> 00:26:13.000
as a community now, for that.

00:26:13.000 --> 00:26:14.000
And it's the same idea,

00:26:14.000 --> 00:26:15.000
is we just find those champions,

00:26:15.000 --> 00:26:16.000
bring them together,

00:26:16.000 --> 00:26:19.000
start having some informal meet-ups,

00:26:19.000 --> 00:26:21.000
and then it comes from there.

00:26:21.000 --> 00:26:25.000
And eventually, the executive or the leadership level

00:26:25.000 --> 00:26:27.000
will say, oh, there is a need for this.

00:26:27.000 --> 00:26:30.000
And then, hopefully, there will be some support

00:26:30.000 --> 00:26:35.000
from actual roles in that position.

00:26:37.000 --> 00:26:41.000
How do you get it so that it's easy to get the people that,

00:26:41.000 --> 00:26:42.000
like, when you're out there,

00:26:42.000 --> 00:26:43.000
you're showing something,

00:26:43.000 --> 00:26:44.000
and you're three or whatever,

00:26:44.000 --> 00:26:45.000
and you're like, that's cool,

00:26:45.000 --> 00:26:46.000
I want to check that out.

00:26:46.000 --> 00:26:48.000
So then you've got all those people.

00:26:48.000 --> 00:26:50.000
But then you've got the people that are like,

00:26:50.000 --> 00:26:52.000
well, I can do this at home.

00:26:52.000 --> 00:26:56.000
So that's kind of where we're at now.

00:26:57.000 --> 00:27:00.000
We don't have something like that.

00:27:00.000 --> 00:27:03.000
So that's kind of where, like,

00:27:03.000 --> 00:27:05.000
those are the hold-downs now.

00:27:05.000 --> 00:27:08.000
It's really a struggle, quite honestly.

00:27:08.000 --> 00:27:09.000
Like, I get them on my team.

00:27:09.000 --> 00:27:11.000
I have no idea what to say.

00:27:11.000 --> 00:27:13.000
I can never do this.

00:27:13.000 --> 00:27:16.000
Yeah, so that is definitely,

00:27:16.000 --> 00:27:20.000
so I put on two hats when I'm dealing with solutions

00:27:20.000 --> 00:27:23.000
where someone's like, oh, well, probably I can do this.

00:27:24.000 --> 00:27:27.000
And a lot of it is, one,

00:27:27.000 --> 00:27:31.000
is where are you looking for the scalability to happen?

00:27:31.000 --> 00:27:35.000
Are you going to be rolling this out to all your clients?

00:27:35.000 --> 00:27:37.000
If you're going to do that,

00:27:37.000 --> 00:27:38.000
well, I'm not going to,

00:27:38.000 --> 00:27:39.000
I'm going to go more on,

00:27:39.000 --> 00:27:41.000
if Power BI does exactly what you need to do,

00:27:41.000 --> 00:27:43.000
I'm going to say go use Power BI.

00:27:43.000 --> 00:27:45.000
If it's going to be, well,

00:27:45.000 --> 00:27:47.000
we need someone that's going to do some

00:27:47.000 --> 00:27:50.000
Bayesian type of modeling,

00:27:50.000 --> 00:27:53.000
or whatnot,

00:27:53.000 --> 00:27:56.000
and, well, then we might go with

00:27:56.000 --> 00:27:58.000
an RStudio type of product

00:27:58.000 --> 00:27:59.000
because we can build the models,

00:27:59.000 --> 00:28:00.000
we can test it,

00:28:00.000 --> 00:28:01.000
we can create some pipelines around it,

00:28:01.000 --> 00:28:03.000
and then we can deploy that.

00:28:03.000 --> 00:28:06.000
So it really depends on what the actual use case is.

00:28:06.000 --> 00:28:07.000
But there are some where you're going to be,

00:28:07.000 --> 00:28:09.000
well, this can do it the same way.

00:28:09.000 --> 00:28:11.000
Then the question is who's going to support it, right?

00:28:11.000 --> 00:28:14.000
So if one single person is like,

00:28:14.000 --> 00:28:17.000
oh, I can build this in open source code,

00:28:17.000 --> 00:28:19.000
I can build a whole end-to-end process,

00:28:19.000 --> 00:28:20.000
then the question is, well,

00:28:20.000 --> 00:28:21.000
how much money do you leave?

00:28:21.000 --> 00:28:23.000
Or if you were to move on to something else,

00:28:23.000 --> 00:28:24.000
who's going to keep the other money?

00:28:24.000 --> 00:28:26.000
Do we have enough people to support that?

00:28:26.000 --> 00:28:28.000
So those are the kind of questions

00:28:28.000 --> 00:28:29.000
and answers I would be giving.

00:28:29.000 --> 00:28:32.000
Well, we can't do it

00:28:32.000 --> 00:28:34.000
in this kind of state.

00:28:34.000 --> 00:28:35.000
Right.

00:28:35.000 --> 00:28:36.000
And that's one piece,

00:28:36.000 --> 00:28:38.000
like how much effort does it take to update it?

00:28:38.000 --> 00:28:40.000
Like, with PowerPoint,

00:28:40.000 --> 00:28:42.000
it's a static type of setup, right?

00:28:42.000 --> 00:28:45.000
So you kind of build your visualization once

00:28:45.000 --> 00:28:47.000
and then it's there, and that's it.

00:28:47.000 --> 00:28:49.000
But how do you get people to do PowerPoint

00:28:49.000 --> 00:28:51.000
to change, I guess?

00:28:51.000 --> 00:28:52.000
Oh, okay.

00:28:52.000 --> 00:28:55.000
So to help motivate people

00:28:55.000 --> 00:28:59.000
to move on to more complex technologies,

00:28:59.000 --> 00:29:02.000
a lot of it comes from a top-down process.

00:29:02.000 --> 00:29:05.000
So one of the things I inherited

00:29:05.000 --> 00:29:08.000
when I joined, coming on with now,

00:29:08.000 --> 00:29:11.000
is a legacy team that builds

00:29:11.000 --> 00:29:15.000
in old data reporting platforms.

00:29:16.000 --> 00:29:19.000
And so, which means that they do a lot of reporting

00:29:19.000 --> 00:29:23.000
but in old languages and old platforms.

00:29:23.000 --> 00:29:25.000
And so one of the things I gave an agenda to

00:29:25.000 --> 00:29:27.000
is, well, we need to move on to the enterprise,

00:29:27.000 --> 00:29:29.000
modern enterprise data architecture,

00:29:29.000 --> 00:29:32.000
which is, for reporting, is Power BI.

00:29:32.000 --> 00:29:35.000
And Databricks for the consumption

00:29:35.000 --> 00:29:37.000
of data processing.

00:29:37.000 --> 00:29:40.000
And so it's that vision of what you need to do.

00:29:40.000 --> 00:29:42.000
They then start doing some workshops

00:29:42.000 --> 00:29:44.000
and Power BI started learning in them,

00:29:44.000 --> 00:29:46.000
and now they're actually starting using them now.

00:29:46.000 --> 00:29:48.000
And now they can actually understand it

00:29:48.000 --> 00:29:50.000
to work with the business on how to build new things

00:29:50.000 --> 00:29:51.000
in Power BI.

00:29:51.000 --> 00:29:55.000
So it's much of a top-down approach.

00:29:55.000 --> 00:29:57.000
I think there was another question back there.

00:29:57.000 --> 00:29:58.000
Yeah?

00:29:58.000 --> 00:29:59.000
Yeah, I have a question about

00:29:59.000 --> 00:30:00.000
what you were previously saying

00:30:00.000 --> 00:30:01.000
about growing a team.

00:30:01.000 --> 00:30:03.000
That latter thing was more of a process.

00:30:03.000 --> 00:30:05.000
Did you end up absorbing some of those people

00:30:05.000 --> 00:30:07.000
into your own team?

00:30:07.000 --> 00:30:10.000
If so, how do you get them out of the policy system?

00:30:10.000 --> 00:30:11.000
Yeah.

00:30:11.000 --> 00:30:12.000
Would you be...

00:30:12.000 --> 00:30:13.000
Yeah, so...

00:30:13.000 --> 00:30:14.000
Maybe summarize the questions,

00:30:14.000 --> 00:30:16.000
if people can't hear.

00:30:16.000 --> 00:30:18.000
So how do we deal with,

00:30:18.000 --> 00:30:20.000
or how are there scenarios

00:30:20.000 --> 00:30:24.000
where we took in those employees

00:30:24.000 --> 00:30:26.000
who started on the ground roots,

00:30:26.000 --> 00:30:27.000
who are now part of the team,

00:30:27.000 --> 00:30:29.000
but now want to be part of the team?

00:30:29.000 --> 00:30:31.000
So a couple things,

00:30:31.000 --> 00:30:34.000
scenarios I've had.

00:30:34.000 --> 00:30:37.000
One is that it's more of an allocation piece.

00:30:37.000 --> 00:30:41.000
They get 25% of their full-time

00:30:42.000 --> 00:30:44.000
job allocation to this team

00:30:44.000 --> 00:30:46.000
that focuses on developing applications

00:30:46.000 --> 00:30:48.000
or whatever in that technology.

00:30:48.000 --> 00:30:49.000
That's one approach.

00:30:49.000 --> 00:30:52.000
The other approach is, again,

00:30:52.000 --> 00:30:54.000
it's a top-down piece.

00:30:54.000 --> 00:30:57.000
This whole group aligned to our vision.

00:30:57.000 --> 00:31:01.000
We had one recently when it came to data products.

00:31:01.000 --> 00:31:03.000
We are a data area,

00:31:03.000 --> 00:31:05.000
a data organization that's focused on building

00:31:05.000 --> 00:31:08.000
and developing and supporting data products.

00:31:08.000 --> 00:31:10.000
But there turns out to be some teams out there

00:31:10.000 --> 00:31:11.000
that did it also,

00:31:11.000 --> 00:31:13.000
that were not aligned to our vision,

00:31:13.000 --> 00:31:15.000
our strategy, our standardizations,

00:31:15.000 --> 00:31:17.000
our pipelines.

00:31:17.000 --> 00:31:20.000
And so from a top-down approach,

00:31:20.000 --> 00:31:22.000
the question came, why?

00:31:22.000 --> 00:31:24.000
Why is there a separate team out there?

00:31:24.000 --> 00:31:27.000
I think they need to be all together with us.

00:31:27.000 --> 00:31:30.000
So then we have that standardization,

00:31:30.000 --> 00:31:33.000
have the exact same support team and all that.

00:31:33.000 --> 00:31:35.000
And so then it just happened.

00:31:35.000 --> 00:31:37.000
You get approved on a top-down approach.

00:31:38.000 --> 00:31:42.000
So it's very much of a mixture of that.

00:31:42.000 --> 00:31:45.000
You can have where it kind of forces everyone

00:31:45.000 --> 00:31:46.000
that wants to do it,

00:31:46.000 --> 00:31:48.000
but you kind of have that forced way.

00:31:48.000 --> 00:31:50.000
Or you have a way to just grouse through

00:31:50.000 --> 00:31:52.000
and get some allocations to the managers.

00:31:57.000 --> 00:31:59.000
So we usually have an hour for the Hangout,

00:31:59.000 --> 00:32:02.000
but this was shortened in between our lunchtime here.

00:32:02.000 --> 00:32:05.000
So I think we have time for two more questions.

00:32:06.000 --> 00:32:08.000
I see Darren had asked,

00:32:08.000 --> 00:32:10.000
since you are in a leadership role,

00:32:10.000 --> 00:32:12.000
what hands-on technical responsibilities

00:32:12.000 --> 00:32:15.000
do you still own and are responsible for?

00:32:15.000 --> 00:32:17.000
And what are you having a hard time letting go

00:32:17.000 --> 00:32:19.000
because you enjoy it so much?

00:32:19.000 --> 00:32:22.000
Or maybe can't find someone to take the ownership?

00:32:22.000 --> 00:32:25.000
Right, so as a chief data officer,

00:32:25.000 --> 00:32:27.000
I am responsible for the complete

00:32:27.000 --> 00:32:29.000
enterprise data architecture,

00:32:29.000 --> 00:32:32.000
so the high-level data flow mapping.

00:32:32.000 --> 00:32:36.000
So how does, from an application or from sources,

00:32:36.000 --> 00:32:39.000
how is that going to flow all the way down

00:32:39.000 --> 00:32:40.000
through all the different systems,

00:32:40.000 --> 00:32:43.000
all the different setups we have,

00:32:43.000 --> 00:32:44.000
all the different environments,

00:32:44.000 --> 00:32:47.000
all the way to creating those reports

00:32:47.000 --> 00:32:51.000
that we need to submit for regulatory purposes?

00:32:51.000 --> 00:32:54.000
How do we have a whole support team around all that?

00:32:54.000 --> 00:32:56.000
How do we cut things up

00:32:56.000 --> 00:32:58.000
depending on different development teams?

00:32:58.000 --> 00:33:00.000
That is my responsibility on determining

00:33:00.000 --> 00:33:02.000
what that's going to look like.

00:33:02.000 --> 00:33:04.000
Then I hand that over to my direct reports

00:33:04.000 --> 00:33:06.000
who then need to operationalize that,

00:33:06.000 --> 00:33:08.000
meaning that they need to take that design

00:33:08.000 --> 00:33:11.000
and say, okay, I am responsible for data engineering.

00:33:14.000 --> 00:33:16.000
From our strategy, we are all Azure shops,

00:33:16.000 --> 00:33:18.000
so whatever my tooling is, I'm allowed to do that.

00:33:18.000 --> 00:33:20.000
Well, it's going to be Databricks.

00:33:20.000 --> 00:33:21.000
Or from a data science perspective,

00:33:21.000 --> 00:33:23.000
it's going to be Posit.

00:33:23.000 --> 00:33:25.000
And then, again, operationalize that,

00:33:25.000 --> 00:33:26.000
then going a little further,

00:33:26.000 --> 00:33:27.000
and how are we setting it up?

00:33:27.000 --> 00:33:29.000
What's the infrastructure going to look like?

00:33:30.000 --> 00:33:33.000
It's very much at me setting up that overall vision,

00:33:33.000 --> 00:33:35.000
some of the different strategy points in there,

00:33:35.000 --> 00:33:37.000
the principles we need to make decisions on,

00:33:37.000 --> 00:33:39.000
and then my direct reports

00:33:39.000 --> 00:33:41.000
will come up with the solutions around that.

00:33:42.000 --> 00:33:43.000
Thank you.

